Part 1 (plotting with ggplot2)

In this exercise, we will plot the unemployment rate for the UK. To solve the exercise, go through the following steps.

  • Download the dataset here.

  • Clean the data by selecting the relevant columns and renaming the columns to more informative names. Name the column denoting the time .

  • Note that in the column date, the day of the month is missing. The date the data is recorded is the first of each month. Change the column to add this information. Hint: mutate(date = paste(date, "01", sep="-")).

  • What classes do the columns in your dataset belong to? Hint: write class(df$date) in the console.

  • To specify that we are working with dates, we need to encode the column date as a date. In the data, we see that the date format is year-month-day. To specify this you can use mutate and date = as.Date(date, format = "%Y-%m-%d"). Check again the classes of the columns in your dataset.

  • What month had the highest average unemployment rate?

  • Create a new column in your dataset called adj which equals No seasonal adjustment if the row is seasonally adjusted and Seasonal adjustment otherwise. Hint: Use the mutate() and ifelse() functions. adj = ifelse(adj == 'Level, rate or quantity series', 'No seasonal adjustment', 'Seasonal adjustment').

Part 2 (Decomposing a time series with dplyr)

In this exercise, you will decompose the unemployment rate of your assigned country. We will use the same dataset as in part 1. To solve the exercise, go through the following steps.

Some dplyr functions

%>% pipe, read as “then do”.

mutate(): create new column or manipulate existing column.

select(): select columns to keep in the dataframe.

rename(): rename column.

filter(): select rows in a dataframe.

group_by(): perform some subsequent operation by group.

  • Create a new column in your dataset called trend using a two-period moving average. The two-period moving average is given by the following formula \[\begin{equation} \text{trend}_t = \frac{1}{5}\sum_{i = t-2}^{t+2} u_i, \end{equation}\] where \(u_i\) denotes the unemployment at time \(i\).

  • Create a new column in your dataset which gives the difference between the unemployment rate and the trend.

  • Keep only rows that are recorded after January 1. 2014. Hint: date>'2014-01-01'.

  • Reproduce the figures below. To combine the three plots, first generate the plots separately and assign them the names p1, p2, p3. Then import the library ggpubr and use the command ggarrange(p1, p2, p3 ,ncol = 1, nrow = 3). You might need to install the library.
